<subSubSection id="C34A6541882DEE43FF62FB0E6EA1FAA7" pageId="5" pageNumber="388" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BEF36CA882DEE43FF62FB0E6EA1FAA7" blockId="5.[151,1437,1184,1570]" pageId="5" pageNumber="388">
<emphasis id="B924EAD8882DEE43FF62FB0E6D0FFB17" bold="true" box="[199,322,1220,1246]" pageId="5" pageNumber="388">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is morphologically close to 
<taxonomicName id="4C504D49882DEE43FC8BFB0F6F8FFB17" authority="Dimitrov, 2022" authorityName="Dimitrov" authorityYear="2022" box="[814,962,1220,1246]" class="Arachnida" family="Agelenidae" genus="Maimuna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="388" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anatolica" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B924EAD8882DEE43FC8BFB0F6F8FFB17" box="[814,962,1220,1246]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="388">M. anatolica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B924EAD8882DEE43FC68FB0E685CFB17" bold="true" box="[973,1041,1220,1246]" pageId="5" pageNumber="388">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A21757A3882DEE43FC68FB0E685CFB17" box="[973,1041,1220,1246]" pageId="5" pageNumber="388" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
by having a similar shape of the conductor and especially the twisted lamellar terminal end of the ventral part of the conductor. The two species can be separated by (1) the shape of the median apophysis, being massive and with irregular shape in 
<taxonomicName id="4C504D49882DEE43FB48FAC76916FAEF" authorityName=": Demir &amp; Seyyar" authorityYear="2017" box="[1261,1371,1293,1318]" class="Arachnida" family="Agelenidae" genus="Maimuna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="388" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cariae">
<emphasis id="B924EAD8882DEE43FB48FAC76916FAEF" box="[1261,1371,1293,1318]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="388">M. cariae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="136B2A4F882DEE43FACFFAC66CEAFA82" captionStart="FIGURES 4–12" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[320,1267,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-31@2.[320,1267,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 4–12. 4–6 Maimuna anatolica sp. n., holotype male, right palp (flipped). 7–9 Maimuna cariae, paratype male, left palp. 10–12 Maimuna vestita, male, left palp. 1,7, 10 ventral 5, 8, 11 retrolateral; 6, 9, 12 prolateral. Scale line: 0.5 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6411052" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6411052/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="388">Figs 7</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="136B2A4F882DEE43FF11FAFA6C9CFA82" box="[180,209,1328,1355]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–27" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1781,1805]" captionTargetBox="[156,1433,181,1758]" captionTargetId="figure-31@4.[151,1435,181,1758]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 21–27. 21–23 Maimuna anatolica sp. n., male holotype. 24–25 Maimuna anatolica sp. n., female paratype. 26 Maimuna cariae, male paratype. 27 Maimuna vestita, male. 21, 26–27 palp, ventral. 22 palp prolateral. 23 palp retrolateral. 24 epigyne, ventral view. 25 vulva, dorsal view. Scale line: 0.5 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6411056" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6411056/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="388">26</figureCitation>
) vs. narrow and pointed apically in 
